#. Tag: title
#: yast2_gui.xml:8
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using &yast;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: meta
#: yast2_gui.xml:10
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configure your system with YaST, a tool providing a graphical interface for all essential installation and system configuration tasks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: date
#: yast2_gui.xml:17
#, no-c-format
msgid "2023-08-21"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: yast2_gui.xml:24
#, no-c-format
msgid "&yast; is a &productname; tool that provides a graphical interface for all essential installation and system configuration tasks. Whether you need to update packages, configure a printer, modify firewall settings, set up an FTP server, or partition a hard disk&mdash;you can do it using &yast;. Written in Ruby, &yast; features an extensible architecture that makes it possible to add new functionality via modules."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: yast2_gui.xml:32
#, no-c-format
msgid "Additional information about &yast; is available on the project's official Web site at <link xlink:href=\"https://yast.opensuse.org/\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: yast2_gui.xml:37
#, no-c-format
msgid "&yast; interface overview"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: yast2_gui.xml:38
#, no-c-format
msgid "&yast; has two graphical interfaces: one for use with graphical desktop environments like KDE and GNOME, and an ncurses-based pseudo-graphical interface for use on systems without an X server (see <xref linkend=\"cha-yast-text\"/> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: yast2_gui.xml:43
#, no-c-format
msgid "In the graphical version of &yast;, all modules in &yast; are grouped by category, and the navigation sidebar allows you to quickly access modules in the desired category. The search field at the top makes it possible to find modules by their names. To find a specific module, enter its name into the search field, and you should see the modules that match the entered string as you type."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: yast2_gui.xml:52
#, no-c-format
msgid "List of installed &yast; modules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: yast2_gui.xml:53
#, no-c-format
msgid "The list of installed modules for the ncurses-based and GUI version of &yast; may differ. Before starting any &yast; module, verify that it is installed for the version of &yast; that you are using."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: yast2_gui.xml:61
#, no-c-format
msgid "&yast; modules and configuration files"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: yast2_gui.xml:62
#, no-c-format
msgid "In &productname; 15, &yast; modules act as a front-end that writes to specific back-end configuration files. Most system-wide settings are stored in <filename> /etc/sysconfig/</filename> . The <literal>sysconfig</literal> module is the heart of &yast; legacy. Many modules write to variables here, which are then read by system scripts during boot or service start. To verify exactly which file was changed during a &yast; session, check the log at <filename>/var/log/YaST2/y2log</filename> .Note that while you can manually edit a file, running a YaST module afterward can sometimes overwrite manual changes if the module does not recognize the manual syntax."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: yast2_gui.xml:67
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following table maps the most common &yast; modules to the primary configuration files they modify:"
msgstr ""

